04732nam a22006015i 9780822385752DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223857527 a10.1515/97808223857522doi  a(DE-B1597)553821  a(OCoLC)1226678905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF3721.3.E25bS29 2004 7aHIS0330002bisacsh1 aSawyer, Suzana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrude Chronicles :bIndigenous Politics, Multinational Oil, and Neoliberalism in Ecuador /cSuzana Sawyer; Gilbert M. Joseph, Emily S. Rosenberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (310 p.) :b28 b&w photos, 6 maps, 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Names -- tOpening -- ti national narratives -- t1. Amazonian Imaginaries -- t2. Crude Excesses -- tii petroleum politics -- t3. Neoliberal Ironies -- t4. Corporate Antipolitics -- tiii raced realities -- t5. Contested Terrain -- t6. Liberal Legal-Scapes -- tClosing: A Plurinational Space -- tNotes -- tAcronyms -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEcuador is the third-largest foreign supplier of crude oil to the western United States. As the source of this oil, the Ecuadorian Amazon has borne the far-reaching social and environmental consequences of a growing U.S. demand for petroleum and the dynamics of economic globalization it necessitates. Crude Chronicles traces the emergence during the 1990s of a highly organized indigenous movement and its struggles against a U.S. oil company and Ecuadorian neoliberal policies. Against the backdrop of mounting government attempts to privatize and liberalize the national economy, Suzana Sawyer shows how neoliberal reforms in Ecuador led to a crisis of governance, accountability, and representation that spurred one of twentieth-century Latin America's strongest indigenous movements.Through her rich ethnography of indigenous marches, demonstrations, occupations, and negotiations, Sawyer tracks the growing sophistication of indigenous politics as Indians subverted, re-deployed, and, at times, capitulated to the dictates and desires of a transnational neoliberal logic. At the same time, she follows the multiple maneuvers and discourses that the multinational corporation and the Ecuadorian state used to circumscribe and contain indigenous opposition. Ultimately, Sawyer reveals that indigenous struggles over land and oil operations in Ecuador were as much about reconfiguring national and transnational inequality-that is, rupturing the silence around racial injustice, exacting spaces of accountability, and rewriting narratives of national belonging-as they were about the material use and extraction of rain-forest resources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxPolitics and government. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxSocial conditions. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectszEcuador. 0aProtest movementszEcuador. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385752zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385752.j